"Sherry R.A., Zhou X., Gu S., Arnone III J.A., Schimel D.S., Verburg P.S., Wallace L.L., Luo Y.","Divergence of reproductive phenology under climate warming",2007,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","104","1",,"198","202",,,10.1073/pnas.0605642104,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33846059773&partnerID=40&md5=1237724a4794690e0f9986d08cd56c18","Department of Botany and Microbiology, University of Oklahoma, Norman, OK 73019, United States; Department of Agronomy, Yangzhou University, Yangzhou 225009, China; Division of Earth and Ecosystem Sciences, Desert Research Institute, Reno, NV 89512, United States; Terrestrial Sciences Section, National Center for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, CO 80305, United States; Department of Botany and Microbiology, University of Oklahoma, 770 Van Vleet Oval, Norman, OK 73019, United States","Sherry, R.A., Department of Botany and Microbiology, University of Oklahoma, Norman, OK 73019, United States, Department of Botany and Microbiology, University of Oklahoma, 770 Van Vleet Oval, Norman, OK 73019, United States; Zhou, X., Department of Botany and Microbiology, University of Oklahoma, Norman, OK 73019, United States; Gu, S., Department of Agronomy, Yangzhou University, Yangzhou 225009, China; Arnone III, J.A., Division of Earth and Ecosystem Sciences, Desert Research Institute, Reno, NV 89512, United States; Schimel, D.S., Terrestrial Sciences Section, National Center for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, CO 80305, United States; Verburg, P.S., Division of Earth and Ecosystem Sciences, Desert Research Institute, Reno, NV 89512, United States; Wallace, L.L., Department of Botany and Microbiology, University of Oklahoma, Norman, OK 73019, United States; Luo, Y., Department of Botany and Microbiology, University of Oklahoma, Norman, OK 73019, United States","Because the flowering and fruiting phenology of plants is sensitive to environmental cues such as temperature and moisture, climate change is likely to alter community-level patterns of reproductive phenology. Here we report a previously unreported phenomenon: experimental warming advanced flowering and fruiting phenology for species that began to flower before the peak of summer heat but delayed reproduction in species that started flowering after the peak temperature in a tallgrass prairie in North America. The warming-induced divergence of flowering and fruiting toward the two ends of the growing season resulted in a gap in the staggered progression of flowering and fruiting in the community during the middle of the season. A double precipitation treatment did not significantly affect flowering and fruiting phenology. Variation among species in the direction and magnitude of their response to warming caused compression and expansion of the reproductive periods of different species, changed the amount of overlap between the reproductive phases, and created possibilities for an altered selective environment to reshape communities in a future warmed world. © 2006 by The National Academy of Sciences of the USA.","Climate change; Global warming; Precipitation","article; climate change; controlled study; environmental temperature; flowering; fruiting; greenhouse effect; heat; moisture; nonhuman; North America; phenology; plant reproduction; precipitation; priority journal; summer; Climate; Flowers; Fruit; Greenhouse Effect; Plant Physiology; Reproduction",,,,,,"Walther, G.-R., Post, E., Convey, P., Menzel, A., Parmesan, C., Beebee, T.R.C., Fromentin, J.-M., Bairlein, F., (2002) Nature, 416, pp. 389-395; Peñuelas, J., Filella, I., (2001) Science, 294, pp. 793-795; Parmesan, C., Yohe, G., (2003) Nature, 421, pp. 37-42; Root, T.L., Price, J.T., Hall, K.R., Schnelder, S.H., Rosenzweig, C., Pounds, J.A., (2003) Nature, 241, pp. 57-60; Myneni, R.B., Keeling, C.D., Tucker, C.J., Asrar, G., Nemani, R.R., (1997) Nature, 386, pp. 698-702; Slayback, D.A., Pinzon, J.E., Los, S.O., Tucker, C.J., (2003